# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: string-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] In computer science, the **Aho–Corasick algorithm** is a string-searching algorithm invented by Alfred V.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] It is a kind of dictionary-matching algorithm that locates elements of a finite set of strings (the "dictionary") within an input text.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The complexity of the algorithm is linear in the length of the strings plus the length of the searched text plus the number of output matches.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] Because all matches are found, multiple matches will be returned for one string location if multiple strings from the dictionary match at that location (e.g. dictionary = a, aa, aaa, aaaa and input string is aaaa).
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] Informally, the algorithm creates a trie using the strings in the dictionary and then constructs a finite-state machine from the trie by adding additional links between the nodes.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] This allows the automaton to transition between string matches without the need for backtracking.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] When the string dictionary is known in advance (e.g. a computer virus database), the construction of the automaton can be performed once off-line and the compiled automaton stored for later use.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] In this case, its run time is linear in the length of the input plus the number of matched entries.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The Aho—Corasick string-matching algorithm formed the basis of the original Unix command fgrep.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] Like many inventions at Bell Labs at the time, the Aho–Corasick algorithm was created serendipitously with a conversation between the two after a seminar by Aho.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] Corasick was an information scientist who got her PhD a year earlier at Lehigh University.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] There, she did her dissertation on securing proprietary data within open systems, through the lens of both the commercial, legal, and government structures and the technical tools that were emerging at the time.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] In a similar realm, at Bell Labs, she was building a tool for researchers to learn about current work being done by government contractors by searching government-provided tapes of publications.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] She had written a primitive keyword-by-keyword search program to find chosen keywords within the tapes, but it scaled poorly with many keywords; One of the bibliographers using her algorithm hit the $600 usage limit on the Bell Labs machines before their search finished.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] She ended up attending a seminar on algorithm design by Aho, and afterwards they got to speaking about her work and this problem.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] Aho suggested improving the efficiency of the program using the approach of the now Aho–Corasick algorithm, and Corasick designed a program based on those insights.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] This lowered the running cost of that bibliographer's search from over $600 to just $25.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] In this example, we will consider a dictionary consisting of the following words: {a, ab, bab, bc, bca, c, caa}.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The graph below is the Aho–Corasick data structure constructed from the specified dictionary, with each row in the table representing a node in the trie, with the column path indicating the (unique) sequence of characters from the root to the node.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The data structure has one node for every prefix of every string in the dictionary.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] So if (bca) is in the dictionary, then there will be nodes for (bca), (bc), (b), and ().
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] If a node is in the dictionary then it is a blue node.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a black directed "child" arc from each node to a node whose name is found by appending one character.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] So there is a black arc from (bc) to (bca).
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a blue directed "suffix" arc from each node to the node that is the longest possible strict suffix of it in the graph.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] For example, for node (caa), its strict suffixes are (aa) and (a) and ().
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The longest of these that exists in the graph is (a).
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] So there is a blue arc from (caa) to (a).
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The blue arcs can be computed in linear time by performing a breadth-first search [potential suffix node will always be at lower level] starting from the root.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The target for the blue arc of a visited node can be found by following its parent's blue arc to its longest suffix node and searching for a child of the suffix node whose character matches that of the visited node.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] If the character does not exist as a child, we can find the next longest suffix (following the blue arc again) and then search for the character.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] We can do this until we either find the character (as child of a node) or we reach the root (which will always be a suffix of every string).
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] There is a green "dictionary suffix" arc from each node to the next node in the dictionary that can be reached by following blue arcs.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] For example, there is a green arc from (bca) to (a) because (a) is the first node in the dictionary (i.e. a blue node) that is reached when following the blue arcs to (ca) and then on to (a).
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The green arcs can be computed in linear time by repeatedly traversing blue arcs until a blue node is found, and memoizing this information.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] At each step, the current node is extended by finding its child, and if that doesn't exist, finding its suffix's child, and if that doesn't work, finding its suffix's suffix's child, and so on, finally ending in the root node if nothing's seen before.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] When the algorithm reaches a node, it outputs all the dictionary entries that end at the current character position in the input text.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] This is done by printing every node reached by following the dictionary suffix links, starting from that node, and continuing until it reaches a node with no dictionary suffix link.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] In addition, the node itself is printed, if it is a dictionary entry.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] The original Aho–Corasick algorithm assumes that the set of search strings is fixed.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] It does not directly apply to applications in which new search strings are added during application of the algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] An example is an interactive indexing program, in which the user goes through the text and highlights new words or phrases to index as they see them.
[src:string-algorithms/aho-corasick-algorithm] Bertrand Meyer introduced an incremental version of the algorithm in which the search string set can be incrementally extended during the search, retaining the algorithmic complexity of the original.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In computer science, the **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** is an efficient string-searching algorithm that is the standard benchmark for practical string-search literature.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The original paper contained static tables for computing the pattern shifts without an explanation of how to produce them.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm for producing the tables was published in a follow-on paper; this paper contained errors which were later corrected by Wojciech Rytter in 1980.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm preprocesses the string being searched for (the pattern), but not the string being searched in (the text).
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It is thus well-suited for applications in which the pattern is much shorter than the text or where it persists across multiple searches.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm uses information gathered during the preprocess step to skip sections of the text, resulting in a lower constant factor than many other string search algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In general, the algorithm runs faster as the pattern length increases.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key features of the algorithm are to match on the tail of the pattern rather than the head, and to skip along the text in jumps of multiple characters rather than searching every single character in the text.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm searches for occurrences of P in T by performing explicit character comparisons at different alignments.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Instead of a brute-force search of all alignments (of which there are ⁠ $n-m+1$ ⁠), Boyer–Moore uses information gained by preprocessing P to skip as many alignments as possible.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Previous to the introduction of this algorithm, the usual way to search within text was to examine each character of the text for the first character of the pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Once that was found the subsequent characters of the text would be compared to the characters of the pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If no match occurred then the text would again be checked character by character in an effort to find a match.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus almost every character in the text needs to be examined.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key insight in this algorithm is that if the end of the pattern is compared to the text, then jumps along the text can be made rather than checking every character of the text.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The reason that this works is that in lining up the pattern against the text, the last character of the pattern is compared to the character in the text.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the characters do not match, there is no need to continue searching backwards along the text.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text does not match any of the characters in the pattern, then the next character in the text to check is located m characters farther along the text, where m is the length of the pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text *is* in the pattern, then a partial shift of the pattern along the text is done to line up along the matching character and the process is repeated.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Jumping along the text to make comparisons rather than checking every character in the text decreases the number of comparisons that have to be made, which is the key to the efficiency of the algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] More formally, the algorithm begins at alignment ⁠ $k=m$ ⁠, so the start of P is aligned with the start of T.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Characters in P and T are then compared starting at index m in P and k in T, moving backward.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The strings are matched from the end of P to the start of P.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons continue until either the beginning of P is reached (which means there is a match) or a mismatch occurs upon which the alignment is shifted forward (to the right) according to the maximum value permitted by a number of rules.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons are performed again at the new alignment, and the process repeats until the alignment is shifted past the end of T, which means no further matches will be found.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The shift rules are implemented as constant-time table lookups, using tables generated during the preprocessing of P.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A shift is calculated by applying two rules: the bad-character rule and the good-suffix rule.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The actual shifting offset is the maximum of the shifts calculated by these rules.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The bad-character rule considers the character in T at which the comparison process failed (assuming such a failure occurred).
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The next occurrence of that character to the left in P is found, and a shift which brings that occurrence in line with the mismatched occurrence in T is proposed.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the mismatched character does not occur to the left in P, a shift is proposed that moves the entirety of P past the point of mismatch.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Methods vary on the exact form the table for the bad-character rule should take, but a simple constant-time lookup solution is as follows: create a 2D table which is indexed first by the index of the character c in the alphabet and second by the index i in the pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This lookup will return the occurrence of c in P with the next-highest index ⁠ $j<i$ ⁠ or -1 if there is no such occurrence.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The proposed shift will then be ⁠ $i-j$ ⁠, with ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠ lookup time and ⁠ $O(km)$ ⁠ space, assuming a finite alphabet of length k.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The C and Java implementations below have a ⁠ $O(k)$ ⁠ space complexity (make_delta1, makeCharTable).
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is the same as the original delta1 and the BMH bad-character table.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This table maps a character at position ⁠ i ⁠ to shift by ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)-1-i$ ⁠, with the last instance—the least shift amount—taking precedence.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] All unused characters are set as ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)$ ⁠ as a sentinel value.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule is markedly more complex in both concept and implementation than the bad-character rule.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Like the bad-character rule, it also exploits the algorithm's feature of comparisons beginning at the end of the pattern and proceeding towards the pattern's start.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule requires two tables: one for use in the general case (where a copy ***t′*** is found), and another for use when the general case returns no meaningful result.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] These tables will be designated L and H respectively.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Both of these tables are constructible in ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ time and use ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ space.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The alignment shift for index i in P is given by ⁠ $m-L[i]$ ⁠ or ⁠ $m-H[i]$ ⁠.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] H should only be used if ⁠ $L[i]$ ⁠ is zero or a match has been found.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 0, no characters matched, the character read was not an N.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Since there are plenty of letters in the pattern that are also not N, we have minimal information here - shifting by 1 is the least interesting result.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 1, we matched the N, and it was preceded by something other than A.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Now look at the pattern starting from the end, where do we have N preceded by something other than A?
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There are two other N's, but both are preceded by A.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] That means no part of the good suffix can be useful to us—shift by the full pattern length 8.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 2: We matched the AN, and it was preceded by not M.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In the middle of the pattern there is a AN preceded by P, so it becomes the shift candidate.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Shifting that AN to the right to line up with our match is a shift of 3.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 3 & up: the matched suffixes do not match anything else in the pattern, but the trailing suffix AN matches the start of the pattern, so the shifts here are all 6.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A simple but important optimization of Boyer–Moore was put forth by Zvi Galil in 1979.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] As opposed to shifting, the Galil rule deals with speeding up the actual comparisons done at each alignment by skipping sections that are known to match.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Suppose that at an alignment *k*1, ***P*** is compared with ***T*** down to character ***c*** of ***T***.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Then if ***P*** is shifted to *k*2 such that its left end is between ***c*** and *k*1, in the next comparison phase a prefix of ***P*** must match the substring ***T***[(*k*2 - *n*)..*k*1].
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus if the comparisons get down to position *k*1 of ***T***, an occurrence of ***P*** can be recorded without explicitly comparing past *k*1.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In addition to increasing the efficiency of Boyer–Moore, the Galil rule is required for proving linear-time execution in the worst case.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Galil rule, in its original version, is only effective for versions that output multiple matches.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It updates the substring range only on ***c*** = 0, i.e. a full match.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A generalized version for dealing with submatches was reported in 1985 as the Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm as presented in the original paper has worst-case running time of ⁠ $O(n+m)$ ⁠ only if the pattern does *not* appear in the text.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This was first proved by Knuth, Morris, and Pratt in 1977, followed by Guibas and Odlyzko in 1980 with an upper bound of 5*n* comparisons in the worst case.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Richard Cole gave a proof with an upper bound of 3*n* comparisons in the worst case in 1991.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There is a simple modification of the BM algorithm which improves the bound to 2*n*.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] When the pattern *does* occur in the text, running time of the original algorithm is ⁠ $O(nm)$ ⁠ in the worst case.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is easy to see when both pattern and text consist solely of the same repeated character.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] However, inclusion of the Galil rule results in linear runtime across all cases.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Knuth, Morris and Pratt also showed that for a *random* text, the average number of character comparisons is bounded by $O\left({\frac {n\log _{k}m}{m}}\right)$ , where k is the alphabet size.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Various implementations exist in different programming languages.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In C++ it is part of the Standard Library since C++17 and Boost provides the generic Boyer–Moore search implementation under the *Algorithm* library.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In Go (programming language) there is an implementation in search.go.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] D (programming language) uses a BoyerMooreFinder for predicate based matching within ranges as a part of the Phobos Runtime Library.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm is also used in GNU's grep.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm is a simplification of the Boyer–Moore algorithm using only the bad-character rule.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm speeds up the process of checking whether a match has occurred at the given alignment by skipping explicit character comparisons.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This uses information gleaned during the pre-processing of the pattern in conjunction with suffix match lengths recorded at each match attempt.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Storing suffix match lengths requires an additional table equal in size to the text being searched.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Raita algorithm improves the performance of Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The searching pattern of particular sub-string in a given string is different from Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and independently discovered by Donald Knuth "a few weeks later" from automata theory.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and Vaughan Pratt published a technical report in 1970.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The three also published the algorithm jointly in 1977.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Independently, in 1969, Matiyasevich discovered a similar algorithm, coded by a two-dimensional Turing machine, while studying a string-pattern-matching recognition problem over a binary alphabet.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This was the first linear-time algorithm for string matching.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A string-matching algorithm wants to find the starting index `m` in string `s` that matches the search word `w`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The most straightforward algorithm, known as the "brute-force" or "naive" algorithm, is to look for a word match at each index `m`, i.e. the position in the string being searched that corresponds to the character `s[m]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At each position `m` the algorithm first checks for equality of the first character in the word being searched, i.e.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a match is found, the algorithm tests the other characters in the word being searched by checking successive values of the word position index, `i`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm retrieves the character `w[i]` in the word being searched and checks for equality of the expression `S[m+i] =?
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If all successive characters match in `W` at position `m`, then a match is found at that position in the search string.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the index `m` reaches the end of the string then there is no match, in which case the search is said to "fail".
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Usually, the trial check will quickly reject the trial match.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are uniformly distributed random letters, then the chance that characters match is 1 in 26.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In most cases, the trial check will reject the match at the initial letter.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The chance that the first two letters will match is 1 in 676 (1 in 26^2 chances of a match over 26 possible letters).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] So if the characters are random, then the expected complexity of searching string `s` of length *n* is on the order of *n* comparisons or *Θ*(*n*).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `s` is 1 million characters and `w` is 1000 characters, then the string search should complete after about 1.04 million character comparisons.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] That expected performance is not guaranteed.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are not random, then checking a trial `m` may take many character comparisons.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The worst case is if the two strings match in all but the last letter.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Imagine that the string `s` consists of 1 million characters that are all *A*, and that the word `w` is 999 *A* characters terminating in a final *B* character.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string-matching algorithm will now examine 1000 characters at each trial position before rejecting the match and advancing the trial position.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string search example would now take about 1000 character comparisons times 1 million positions for 1 billion character comparisons.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the length of `w` is *k*, then the worst-case performance is *O*(*k*⋅*n*).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The KMP algorithm has a better worst-case performance than the straightforward algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP spends a little time precomputing a table (on the order of the size of `w`, *O*(*k*)), and then it uses that table to do an efficient search of the string in *O*(*n*).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The difference is that KMP makes use of previous match information that the straightforward algorithm does not.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In the example above, when KMP sees a trial match fail on the 1000th character (`i` = 999) because `s[m + 999] ≠ w[999]`, it will increment `m` by 1, but it will know that the first 998 characters at the new position already match.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP matched 999 *A* characters before discovering a mismatch at the 1000th character (position 999).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Advancing the trial match position `m` by one throws away the first *A*, so KMP knows there are 998 *A* characters that match `w` and does not retest them; that is, KMP sets `i` to 998.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP maintains its knowledge in the precomputed table and two state variables.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] When KMP discovers a mismatch, the table determines how much KMP will increase (variable `m`) and where it will resume testing (variable `i`).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To illustrate the algorithm's details, consider a (relatively artificial) run of the algorithm, where `W` = "ABCDABD" and `S` = "ABC ABCDAB ABCDABCDABDE".
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In each step the algorithm compares `S[m+i]` with `W[i]` and increments `i` if they are equal.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm compares successive characters of `W` to "parallel" characters of `S`, moving from one to the next by incrementing `i` if they match.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, in the fourth step `S[3] = ' '` does not match `W[3] = 'D'`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Rather than beginning to search again at `S[1]`, we note that no `'A'` occurs between positions 1 and 2 in `S`; hence, having checked all those characters previously (and knowing they matched the corresponding characters in `W`), there is no chance of finding the beginning of a match.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm sets `m = 3` and `i = 0`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here, `i` increments through a nearly complete match `"ABCDAB"` until `i = 6` giving a mismatch at `W[6]` and `S[10]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, just prior to the end of the current partial match, there was that substring `"AB"` that could be the beginning of a new match, so the algorithm must take this into consideration.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As these characters match the two characters prior to the current position, those characters need not be checked again; the algorithm sets `m = 8` (the start of the initial prefix) and `i = 2` (signaling the first two characters match) and continues matching.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the algorithm not only omits previously matched characters of `S` (the `"AB"`), but also previously matched characters of `W` (the prefix `"AB"`).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This search at the new position fails immediately because `W[2]` (a `'C'`) does not match `S[10]` (a `' '`).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As in the first trial, the mismatch causes the algorithm to return to the beginning of `W` and begins searching at the mismatched character position of `S`: `m = 10`, reset `i = 0`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The match at `m=10` fails immediately, so the algorithm next tries `m = 11` and `i = 0`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Once again, the algorithm matches `"ABCDAB"`, but the next character, `'C'`, does not match the final character `'D'` of the word `W`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Reasoning as before, the algorithm sets `m = 15`, to start at the two-character string `"AB"` leading up to the current position, set `i = 2`, and continue matching from the current position.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This time the match is complete, and the first character of the match is `S[15]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The above example contains all the elements of the algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] For the moment, we assume the existence of a "partial match" table `T`, described below, which indicates where we need to look for the start of a new match when a mismatch is found.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The entries of `T` are constructed so that if we have a match starting at `S[m]` that fails when comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match will start at index `m + i - T[i]` in `S` (that is, `T[i]` is the amount of "backtracking" we need to do after a mismatch).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The following is a sample pseudocode implementation of the KMP search algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Assuming the prior existence of the table `T`, the search portion of the Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm has complexity *O*(*n*), where *n* is the length of `S` and the *O* is big-O notation.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Except for the fixed overhead incurred in entering and exiting the function, all the computations are performed in the `**while**` loop.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To bound the number of iterations of this loop; observe that `T` is constructed so that if a match which had begun at `S[m]` fails while comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match must begin at `S[m + (i - T[i])]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In particular, the next possible match must occur at a higher index than `m`, so that `T[i] < i`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This fact implies that the loop can execute at most 2*n* times, since at each iteration it executes one of the two branches in the loop.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The first branch invariably increases `i` and does not change `m`, so that the index `m + i` of the currently scrutinized character of `S` is increased.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The second branch adds `i - T[i]` to `m`, and as we have seen, this is always a positive number.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the location `m` of the beginning of the current potential match is increased.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At the same time, the second branch leaves `m + i` unchanged, for `m` gets `i - T[i]` added to it, and immediately after `T[i]` gets assigned as the new value of `i`, hence `new_m + new_i = old_m + old_i - T[old_i] + T[old_i] = old_m + old_i`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the loop executes at most 2*n* times, showing that the time complexity of the search algorithm is *O*(*n*).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here is another way to think about the runtime: Let us say we begin to match `W` and `S` at position `i` and `p`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `W` exists as a substring of `S` at p, then `W[0..m] = S[p..p+m]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon success, that is, the word and the text matched at the positions (`W[i] = S[p+i]`), we increase `i` by 1.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon failure, that is, the word and the text do not match at the positions (`W[i] ≠ S[p+i]`), the text pointer is kept still, while the word pointer is rolled back a certain amount (`i = T[i]`, where `T` is the jump table), and we attempt to match `W[T[i]]` with `S[p+i]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The maximum number of roll-back of `i` is bounded by `i`, that is to say, for any failure, we can only roll back as much as we have progressed up to the failure.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The goal of the table is to allow the algorithm not to match any character of `S` more than once.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In other words, we "pre-search" the pattern itself and compile a list of all possible fallback positions that bypass a maximum of hopeless characters while not sacrificing any potential matches in doing so.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence `T[i]` is exactly the length of the longest possible *proper* initial segment of `W` which is also a segment of the substring ending at `W[i - 1]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We use the convention that the empty string has length 0.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since a mismatch at the very start of the pattern is a special case (there is no possibility of backtracking), we set `T[0] = -1`, as discussed below.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We consider the example of `W = "ABCDABD"` first.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We will see that it follows much the same pattern as the main search, and is efficient for similar reasons.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To find `T[1]`, we must discover a proper suffix of `"A"` which is also a prefix of pattern `W`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But there are no proper suffixes of `"A"`, so we set `T[1] = 0`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However "B" is not a prefix of the pattern `W`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Continuing to `T[3]`, we first check the proper suffix of length 1, and as in the previous case it fails.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence at each stage, the shortcut rule is that one needs to consider checking suffixes of a given size m+1 only if a valid suffix of size m was found at the previous stage (i.e.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `T[x] = m`) and should not bother to check m+2, m+3, etc.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, we need not even concern ourselves with substrings having length 2, and as in the previous case the sole one with length 1 fails, so `T[3] = 0`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We pass to the subsequent `W[4]`, `'A'`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The same logic shows that the longest substring we need to consider has length 1, and as in the previous case it fails since "D" is not a prefix of `W`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But instead of setting `T[4] = 0`, we can do better by noting that `W[4] = W[0]`, and also that a look-up of `T[4]` implies the corresponding `S` character, `S[m+4]`, was a mismatch and therefore `S[m+4] ≠ 'A'`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus there is no point in restarting the search at `S[m+4]`; we should begin at 1 position ahead.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This means that we may shift pattern `W` by match length plus one character, so `T[4] = -1`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Considering now the next character, `W[5]`, which is `'B'`: though by inspection the longest substring would appear to be `'A'`, we still set `T[5] = 0`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The reasoning is similar to why `T[4] = -1`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `W[5]` itself extends the prefix match begun with `W[4]`, and we can assume that the corresponding character in `S`, `S[m+5] ≠ 'B'`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Finally, we see that the next character in the ongoing segment starting at `W[4] = 'A'` would be `'B'`, and indeed this is also `W[5]`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Furthermore, the same argument as above shows that we need not look before `W[4]` to find a segment for `W[6]`, so that this is it, and we take `T[6] = 2`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The example above illustrates the general technique for assembling the table with a minimum of fuss.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The principle is that of the overall search: most of the work was already done in getting to the current position, so very little needs to be done in leaving it.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The only minor complication is that the logic which is correct late in the string erroneously gives non-proper substrings at the beginning.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This necessitates some initialization code.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The time (and space) complexity of the table algorithm is $O(k)$ , where k is the length of `W`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Combined, the outer and inner loops take at most $2k-2$ iterations.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This corresponds to $O(k)$ time complexity using the Big O notation.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since the two portions of the algorithm have, respectively, complexities of `O(k)` and `O(n)`, the complexity of the overall algorithm is `O(n + k)`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] These complexities are independent of how many repetitive patterns are in `W` or `S`.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] It is known that the delay, that is the number of times a symbol of the text is compared to symbols of the pattern, is less than $\lfloor \log _{\Phi }(k+1)\rfloor$ , where Φ is the golden ration $(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2$ .
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In 1993, an algorithm was given that has a delay bounded by $\min(1+\lfloor \log _{2}k\rfloor ,|\Sigma |)$ where Σ is the size of the alphabet (of the pattern).
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A real-time version of KMP can be implemented using a separate failure function table for each character in the alphabet.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a mismatch occurs on character x in the text, the failure function table for character x is consulted for the index i in the pattern at which the mismatch took place.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This will return the length of the longest substring ending at i matching a prefix of the pattern, with the added condition that the character after the prefix is x .
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] With this restriction, character x in the text need not be checked again in the next phase, and so only a constant number of operations are executed between the processing of each index of the text.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This satisfies the real-time computing restriction.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Booth's algorithm uses a modified version of the KMP preprocessing function to find the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
[src:string-algorithms/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The failure function is progressively calculated as the string is rotated.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] In computer science, the **Rabin–Karp algorithm** or **Karp–Rabin algorithm** is a string-searching algorithm created by Richard M.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Rabin (1987) that uses hashing to find an exact match of a pattern string in a text.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] It uses a rolling hash to quickly filter out positions of the text that cannot match the pattern, and then checks for a match at the remaining positions.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Generalizations of the same idea can be used to find more than one match of a single pattern, or to find matches for more than one pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] To find a single match of a single pattern, the expected time of the algorithm is linear in the combined length of the pattern and text, although its worst-case time complexity is the product of the two lengths.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] To find multiple matches, the expected time is linear in the input lengths, plus the combined length of all the matches, which could be greater than linear.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] In contrast, the Aho–Corasick algorithm can find all matches of multiple patterns in worst-case time and space linear in the input length and the number of matches (instead of the total length of the matches).
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] A practical application of the algorithm is detecting plagiarism.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Given source material, the algorithm can rapidly search through a paper for instances of sentences from the source material, ignoring details such as case and punctuation.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Because of the abundance of the sought strings, single-string searching algorithms are impractical.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] A naive string matching algorithm compares the given pattern against all positions in the given text.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Each comparison takes time proportional to the length of the pattern, and the number of positions is proportional to the length of the text.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Therefore, the worst-case time for such a method is proportional to the product of the two lengths.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] In many practical cases, this time can be significantly reduced by cutting short the comparison at each position as soon as a mismatch is found, but this idea cannot guarantee any speedup.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm instead achieves its speedup by using a hash function to quickly perform an approximate check for each position, and then only performing an exact comparison at the positions that pass this approximate check.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] A hash function is a function which converts every string into a numeric value, called its *hash value*; for example, we might have `hash("hello")=5`.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] If two strings are equal, their hash values are also equal.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] For a well-designed hash function, the inverse is true, in an approximate sense: strings that are unequal are very unlikely to have equal hash values.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm proceeds by computing, at each position of the text, the hash value of a string starting at that position with the same length as the pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] If this hash value equals the hash value of the pattern, it performs a full comparison at that position.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] In order for this to work well, the hash function should be selected randomly from a family of hash functions that are unlikely to produce many false positives, that is, positions of the text which have the same hash value as the pattern but do not actually match the pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] These positions contribute to the running time of the algorithm unnecessarily, without producing a match.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Additionally, the hash function used should be a rolling hash, a hash function whose value can be quickly updated from each position of the text to the next.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Recomputing the hash function from scratch at each position would be too slow.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Lines 2, 4, and 6 each require O(*m*) time.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] However, line 2 is only executed once, and line 6 is only executed if the hash values match, which is unlikely to happen more than a few times.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Line 5 is executed O(*n*) times, but each comparison only requires constant time, so its impact is O(*n*).
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Naively computing the hash value for the substring `s[i+1..i+m]` requires O(*m*) time because each character is examined.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Since the hash computation is done on each loop, the algorithm with a naive hash computation requires O(*mn*) time, the same complexity as a straightforward string matching algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] For speed, the hash must be computed in constant time.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The trick is the variable `hs` already contains the previous hash value of `s[i..i+m-1]`.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] If that value can be used to compute the next hash value in constant time, then computing successive hash values will be fast.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The trick can be exploited using a rolling hash.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] A rolling hash is a hash function specially designed to enable this operation.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] A trivial (but not very good) rolling hash function just adds the values of each character in the substring.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] This simple function works, but will result in statement 5 being executed more often than other more sophisticated rolling hash functions such as those discussed in the next section.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Good performance requires a good hashing function for the encountered data.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] If the hashing is poor (such as producing the same hash value for every input), then line 6 would be executed O(*n*) times (i.e. on every iteration of the loop).
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Because character-by-character comparison of strings with length *m* takes O(*m*) time, the whole algorithm then takes a worst-case O(*mn*) time.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The key to the Rabin–Karp algorithm's performance is the efficient computation of hash values of the successive substrings of the text.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin fingerprint is a popular and effective rolling hash function.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The hash function described here is not a Rabin fingerprint, but it works equally well.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] It treats every substring as a number in some base, the base being usually the size of the character set.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Technically, this algorithm is only similar to the true number in a non-decimal system representation, since for example we could have the "base" less than one of the "digits".
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] See hash function for a much more detailed discussion.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The essential benefit achieved by using a rolling hash such as the Rabin fingerprint is that it is possible to compute the hash value of the next substring from the previous one by doing only a constant number of operations, independent of the substrings' lengths.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] We can then compute the hash of the next substring, "bra", from the hash of "abr" by subtracting the number added for the first 'a' of "abr", i.e.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] 97 × 2562, multiplying by the base and adding for the last a of "bra", i.e.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] If the substrings in question are long, this algorithm achieves great savings compared with many other hashing schemes.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Theoretically, there exist other algorithms that could provide convenient recomputation, e.g. multiplying together ASCII values of all characters so that shifting substring would only entail dividing the previous hash by the first character value, then multiplying by the new last character's value.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The limitation, however, is the limited size of the integer data type and the necessity of using modular arithmetic to scale down the hash results.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Meanwhile, naive hash functions do not produce large numbers quickly, but, just like adding ASCII values, are likely to cause many hash collisions and hence slow down the algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] Hence the described hash function is typically the preferred one in the Rabin–Karp algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm is inferior for single pattern searching to Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm, Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and other faster single pattern string searching algorithms because of its slow worst case behavior.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] However, it is a useful algorithm for multiple pattern search.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] We assume all the substrings have a fixed length *m*.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] A naïve way to search for *k* patterns is to repeat a single-pattern search taking O(*n*+*m*) time, totaling in O((*n*+*m*)*k*) time.
[src:string-algorithms/rabin-karp-algorithm] In contrast, the above algorithm can find all *k* patterns in O(*n*+*km*) expected time, assuming that a hash table check works in O(1) expected time.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] A **string-searching algorithm**, sometimes called **string-matching algorithm**, is an algorithm that searches a body of text for portions that match by pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In practice, the method of feasible string-search algorithm may be affected by the string encoding.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In particular, if a variable-width encoding is in use, then it may be slower to find the *N*th character, perhaps requiring time proportional to *N*.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] This may significantly slow some search algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] One of many possible solutions is to search for the sequence of code units instead, but doing so may produce false matches unless the encoding is specifically designed to avoid it.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] The most basic case of string searching involves one (often very long) string, sometimes called the *haystack*, and one (often very short) string, sometimes called the *needle*.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] The goal is to find one or more occurrences of the needle within the haystack.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] One might request the first occurrence of "to", which is the fourth word; or all occurrences, of which there are 3; or the last, which is the fifth word from the end.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Very commonly, however, various constraints are added.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might want to match the "needle" only where it consists of one (or more) complete words—perhaps defined as *not* having other letters immediately adjacent on either side.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In that case a search for "hew" or "low" should fail for the example sentence above, even though those literal strings do occur.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Another common example involves "normalization".
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Finally, for strings that represent natural language, aspects of the language itself become involved.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might wish to find all occurrences of a "word" despite it having alternate spellings, prefixes or suffixes, etc.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Another more complex type of search is regular expression searching, where the user constructs a pattern of characters or other symbols, and any match to the pattern should fulfill the search.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] where the "?" conventionally makes the preceding character ("u") optional.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] This article mainly discusses algorithms for the simpler kinds of string searching.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] A similar problem introduced in the field of bioinformatics and genomics is the maximal exact matching (MEM).
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Given two strings, MEMs are common substrings that cannot be extended left or right without causing a mismatch.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] A simple and inefficient way to see where one string occurs inside another is to check at each index, one by one.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] First, we see if there is a copy of the needle starting at the first character of the haystack; if not, we look to see if there's a copy of the needle starting at the second character of the haystack, and so forth.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In this approach, backtracking is avoided by constructing a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that recognizes a stored search string.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] These are expensive to construct—they are usually created using the powerset construction—but are very quick to use.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] For example, the DFA shown to the right recognizes the word "MOMMY".
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] This approach is frequently generalized in practice to search for arbitrary regular expressions.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Knuth–Morris–Pratt computes a DFA that recognizes inputs with the string to search for as a suffix, Boyer–Moore starts searching from the end of the needle, so it can usually jump ahead a whole needle-length at each step.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Baeza–Yates keeps track of whether the previous *j* characters were a prefix of the search string, and is therefore adaptable to fuzzy string searching.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] The bitap algorithm is an application of Baeza–Yates' approach.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Faster search algorithms preprocess the text.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] After building a substring index, for example a suffix tree or suffix array, the occurrences of a pattern can be found quickly.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] As an example, a suffix tree can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, and all z occurrences of a pattern can be found in $O(m)$ time under the assumption that the alphabet has a constant size and all inner nodes in the suffix tree know what leaves are underneath them.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] The latter can be accomplished by running a DFS algorithm from the root of the suffix tree.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Some search methods, for instance trigram search, are intended to find a "closeness" score between the search string and the text rather than a "match/non-match".
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] These are sometimes called "fuzzy" searches.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] The various algorithms can be classified by the number of patterns each uses.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *m* is the length of the pattern, *n* the length of the searchable text, and *k* = |Σ| is the size of the alphabet.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] The **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** has been the standard benchmark for the practical string-search literature.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *M* is the length of the longest pattern, *m* their total length, *n* the length of the searchable text, *o* the number of occurrences.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Naturally, the patterns can not be enumerated finitely in this case.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] They are represented usually by a regular grammar or regular expression.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Other classification approaches are possible.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] One of the most common uses preprocessing as main criteria.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In real-time string matching, one requires the matcher to output a response after reading each character of the text, that indicates whether this is the last character of a match.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] The response has to be given within constant time.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] For the more lenient version, if one does not mind that the preprocessing time and memory requirement dependend on the size of the alphabet, a real-time solution is provided by automaton matching.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Zvi Galil developed a method to turn certain algorithms into real-time algorithms, and applied it to produce a variant of the KMP matcher that runs in real time under the strict requirement.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In this version of the string searching problem, there is a special symbol, ø (read: don't care), which can match any other symbol (including another ø).
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Don't care symbols can appear either in the pattern or in the text.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] In 2002, an algorithm for this problem that runs in $O(n\log m)$ time has been given by Richard Cole and Ramesh Hariharan, improving on a solution from 1973 by Fischer and Paterson that has complexity $O(n\log m\log k)$ , where *k* is the size of the alphabet.
[src:string-algorithms/string-searching-algorithm] Another algorithm, claimed simpler, has been proposed by Clifford and Clifford.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] In computer science, a **suffix array** is a sorted array of all suffixes of a string.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] It is a data structure used in, among others, full-text indices, data-compression algorithms, and the field of bibliometrics.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Suffix arrays were introduced by Manber & Myers (1990) as a simple, space efficient alternative to suffix trees.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] They had independently been discovered by Gaston Gonnet in 1987 under the name *PAT array* (Gonnet, Baeza-Yates & Snider 1992).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Li, Li & Huo (2016) gave the first in-place ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ time suffix array construction algorithm that is optimal both in time and space, where *in-place* means that the algorithm only needs ${\mathcal {O}}(1)$ additional space beyond the input string and the output suffix array.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Enhanced suffix arrays (ESAs) are suffix arrays with additional tables that reproduce the full functionality of suffix trees preserving the same time and memory complexity.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] A sorted array of only some (rather than all) suffixes of a string is called a sparse suffix array.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Let $S=S[1]S[2]...S[n]$ be an ${\textstyle n}$ -string and let $S[i,j]$ denote the substring of S ranging from i to j inclusive.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The suffix array A of S is now defined to be an array of integers providing the starting positions of suffixes of S in lexicographical order.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] This means, an entry $A[i]$ contains the starting position of the i -th smallest suffix in S and thus for all $1\leq i\leq n$ : $S[A[i-1],n]<S[A[i],n]$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Each suffix of S shows up in A exactly once.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] These strings are sorted (as in a paper dictionary), before their starting positions (integer indices) are saved in A .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The text ends with the special sentinel letter `$` that is unique and lexicographically smaller than any other character.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] So for example, $A[3]$ contains the value 4, and therefore refers to the suffix starting at position 4 within S , which is the suffix `ana$`.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] It has been shown that every suffix tree algorithm can be systematically replaced with an algorithm that uses a suffix array enhanced with additional information (such as the LCP array) and solves the same problem in the same time complexity.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Advantages of suffix arrays over suffix trees include improved space requirements, simpler linear time construction algorithms (e.g., compared to Ukkonen's algorithm) and improved cache locality.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Suffix arrays were introduced by Manber & Myers (1990) in order to improve over the space requirements of suffix trees: Suffix arrays store n integers.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Assuming an integer requires 4 bytes, a suffix array requires $4n$ bytes in total.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] This is significantly less than the $20n$ bytes which are required by a careful suffix tree implementation.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] However, in certain applications, the space requirements of suffix arrays may still be prohibitive.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Analyzed in bits, a suffix array requires ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ space, whereas the original text over an alphabet of size $\sigma$ only requires ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log \sigma )$ bits.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] For a human genome with $\sigma =4$ and $n=3.4\times 10^{9}$ the suffix array would therefore occupy about 16 times more memory than the genome itself.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Such discrepancies motivated a trend towards compressed suffix arrays and BWT-based compressed full-text indices such as the FM-index.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] These data structures require only space within the size of the text or even less.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] A suffix tree can be built in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ and can be converted into a suffix array by traversing the tree depth-first also in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ , so there exist algorithms that can build a suffix array in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] A naive approach to construct a suffix array is to use a comparison-based sorting algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] These algorithms require ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ suffix comparisons, but a suffix comparison runs in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ time, so the overall runtime of this approach is ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2}\log n)$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] More advanced algorithms take advantage of the fact that the suffixes to be sorted are not arbitrary strings but related to each other.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] One of the first algorithms to achieve all goals is the SA-IS algorithm of Nong, Zhang & Chan (2009).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The algorithm is also rather simple (< 100 LOC) and can be enhanced to simultaneously construct the LCP array.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The SA-IS algorithm is one of the fastest known suffix array construction algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] A careful implementation by Yuta Mori outperforms most other linear or super-linear construction approaches.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] A well-known recursive algorithm for integer alphabets is the *DC3 / skew* algorithm of Kärkkäinen & Sanders (2003).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] It runs in linear time and has successfully been used as the basis for parallel and external memory suffix array construction algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] (2010) proposes an algorithm for updating the suffix array of a text that has been edited instead of rebuilding a new suffix array from scratch.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] In practical open source work, a commonly used routine for suffix array construction was qsufsort, based on the 1999 Larsson-Sadakane algorithm.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] This routine has been superseded by Yuta Mori's DivSufSort, "the fastest known suffix sorting algorithm in main memory" as of 2017.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] It too can be modified to compute an LCP array.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] It uses a induced copying combined with Itoh-Tanaka.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] In 2021 a faster implementation of the algorithm was presented by Ilya Grebnov which in average showed 65% performance improvement over DivSufSort implementation on the Silesia corpus.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The concept of a suffix array can be extended to more than one string.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] This is called a generalized suffix array (or GSA), a suffix array that contains all suffixes for a set of strings (for example, $S=S_{1},S_{2},S_{3},...,S_{k}$ and is lexicographically sorted with all suffixes of each string.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The suffix array of a string can be used as an index to quickly locate every occurrence of a substring pattern P within the string S .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Finding every occurrence of the pattern is equivalent to finding every suffix that begins with the substring.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Thanks to the lexicographical ordering, these suffixes will be grouped together in the suffix array and can be found efficiently with two binary searches.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Finding the substring pattern P of length m in the string S of length n takes ${\mathcal {O}}(m\log n)$ time, given that a single suffix comparison needs to compare m characters.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Manber & Myers (1990) describe how this bound can be improved to ${\mathcal {O}}(m+\log n)$ time using LCP information.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The idea is that a pattern comparison does not need to re-compare certain characters, when it is already known that these are part of the longest common prefix of the pattern and the current search interval.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Abouelhoda, Kurtz & Ohlebusch (2004) improve the bound even further and achieve a search time of ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ for constant alphabet size, as known from suffix trees.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Suffix sorting algorithms can be used to compute the Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The BWT requires sorting of all cyclic permutations of a string.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] If this string ends in a special end-of-string character that is lexicographically smaller than all other character (i.e., $), then the order of the sorted rotated BWT matrix corresponds to the order of suffixes in a suffix array.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The BWT can therefore be computed in linear time by first constructing a suffix array of the text and then deducing the BWT string: $BWT[i]=S[A[i]-1]$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Suffix arrays can also be used to look up substrings in example-based machine translation, demanding much less storage than a full phrase table as used in Statistical machine translation.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Many additional applications of the suffix array require the LCP array.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Some of these are detailed in the application section of the latter.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Suffix trees are powerful data structures that have wide application in areas of pattern and string matching, indexing and textual statistics.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] However, it occupies a significant amount of space and thus has a drawback in many real-time applications that require processing a considerably large amount of data like genome analysis.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] To overcome this drawback, the Enhanced Suffix Array was developed.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] It is a data structure consisting of a suffix array and an additional table called the child table that contains the information about the parent-child relationship between the nodes in the suffix tree.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The node branching data structure for this tree is a linked list.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Enhanced suffix arrays are superior to suffix trees in terms of both space efficiency and time complexity and are easy to implement.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Moreover, they can be applied to any algorithm that uses a suffix tree by using an abstract concept called LCP-interval trees.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The time complexity for searching a pattern of length m in an enhanced suffix array is ${\mathcal {O}}(m|\Sigma |)$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] 2. lcp array lcp[1,...n]: It is an array of n integers that maintains the lengths of the longest common prefix of two consecutive suffixes stored in the pos array.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The length of the longest common prefix of pos[i − 1] and pos[i] is stored in lcp[i],where 2 ≤ i ≤ n.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The lcp-interval portrays the same parent-child relationship as that among the associated nodes in the suffix tree of S.This shows that if the corresponding node of [i..j] is a child of the corresponding node of [k..l], a lcp-interval [i..j] is a child interval of another lcp-interval [k..l].
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] If [k..l] is a child interval of [i..j], a lcp-interval [i..j] is the parent interval of a lcp-interval [k..l].
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The child table *cldtab* is composed of three n arrays, *up*, *down* and *nextlIndex*.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The information about the edges of the corresponding suffix tree is stored and maintained by the *up* and *down* arrays.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The *nextlIndex* array stores the links in the linked list used for node branching the suffix tree.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The initial index of the second child interval of the longest lcp-interval, starting at index *i* is stored in the element *down[i]*.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] If and only if the interval is neither the first child nor the final child of its parent, the element *nextlIndex[i]* contains the first index of the next sibling interval of the longest lcp-interval, starting at index *i*.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] By performing a bottom-up traversal of the lcp-interval of the tree, the child table can be constructed in linear time.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The *up/down* values and the *nextlIndex* values can be computed separately by using two distinct algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The suffix links for an enhanced suffix array can be computed by generating the suffix link interval [*1,..,r*] for each [i,..j] interval during the preprocessing.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The left and right elements l and r of the interval are maintained in the first index of [i,..,j].
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The table for this interval ranges from 0 to n.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The suffix link table is constructed by the left-to-right breadth-first traversal of the lcp-interval tree.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] Every time an *l*-interval is computed, it is added to the list of l-intervals, which is referred to as the l-list.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] When the lcp-value > 0, for every *l*-interval[i,..,j] in the list, link[i] is calculated.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The interval [*l*,..,*r*] is computed by a binary search in(*l*-1)-list, where *l* is the largest left boundary amongst all the *l*-1 intervals.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The suffix link interval of [i,..j] is represented by this interval[*l,..,r*].
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-array] The values *l* and *r* are ultimately stored in the first index of [i,..,j].
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] In computer science, a **suffix tree** (also called **PAT tree** or, in an earlier form, **position tree**) is a compressed trie containing all the suffixes of the given text as their keys and positions in the text as their values.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Suffix trees allow particularly fast implementations of many important string operations.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The construction of such a tree for the string S takes time and space linear in the length of S .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Once constructed, several operations can be performed quickly, such as locating a substring in S , locating a substring if a certain number of mistakes are allowed, and locating matches for a regular expression pattern.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Suffix trees also provided one of the first linear-time solutions for the longest common substring problem.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] These speedups come at a cost: storing a string's suffix tree typically requires significantly more space than storing the string itself.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The concept was first introduced by Weiner (1973).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Rather than the suffix $S[i..n]$ , Weiner stored in his trie the *prefix identifier* for each position, that is, the shortest string starting at i and occurring only once in S .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] His *Algorithm D* takes an uncompressed trie for $S[k+1..n]$ and extends it into a trie for $S[k..n]$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] This way, starting from the trivial trie for $S[n..n]$ , a trie for $S[1..n]$ can be built by $n-1$ successive calls to Algorithm D; however, the overall run time is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Weiner's *Algorithm B* maintains several auxiliary data structures, to achieve an overall run time linear in the size of the constructed trie.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The latter can still be $O(n^{2})$ nodes, e.g. for $S=a^{n}b^{n}a^{n}b^{n}\$.$ Weiner's *Algorithm C* finally uses compressed tries to achieve linear overall storage size and run time.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Donald Knuth subsequently characterized the latter as "Algorithm of the Year 1973" according to his student Vaughan Pratt.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The text book Aho, Hopcroft & Ullman (1974, Sect.9.5) reproduced Weiner's results in a simplified and more elegant form, introducing the term *position tree*.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] McCreight (1976) was the first to build a (compressed) trie of all suffixes of S .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Although the suffix starting at i is usually longer than the prefix identifier, their path representations in a compressed trie do not differ in size.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] On the other hand, McCreight could dispense with most of Weiner's auxiliary data structures; only suffix links remained.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Ukkonen (1995) further simplified the construction.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] He provided the first online-construction of suffix trees, now known as Ukkonen's algorithm, with running time that matched the then fastest algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] These algorithms are all linear-time for a constant-size alphabet, and have worst-case running time of $O(n\log n)$ in general.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Farach (1997) gave the first suffix tree construction algorithm that is optimal for all alphabets.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] In particular, this is the first linear-time algorithm for strings drawn from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Farach's algorithm has become the basis for new algorithms for constructing both suffix trees and suffix arrays, for example, in external memory, compressed, succinct, etc.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Except for the root, every internal node has at least two children.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Each edge is labelled with a non-empty substring of S .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] No two edges starting out of a node can have string-labels beginning with the same character.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The string obtained by concatenating all the string-labels found on the path from the root to leaf i spells out suffix $S[i..n]$ , for i from 1 to n .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] If a suffix of S is also the prefix of another suffix, such a tree does not exist for the string.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] For example, in the string *abcbc*, the suffix *bc* is also a prefix of the suffix *bcbc*.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] In such a case, the path spelling out *bc* will not end in a leaf, violating the fifth rule.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] To fix this problem, S is padded with a terminal symbol not seen in the string (usually denoted `$`).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] This ensures that no suffix is a prefix of another, and that there will be n leaf nodes, one for each of the n suffixes of S .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Since all internal non-root nodes are branching, there can be at most $n-1$ such nodes, and $n+(n-1)+1=2n$ nodes in total ( n leaves, $n-1$ internal non-root nodes, 1 root).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] A generalized suffix tree is a suffix tree made for a set of strings instead of a single string.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] It represents all suffixes from this set of strings.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Each string must be terminated by a different termination symbol.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] A suffix tree for a string S of length n can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, if the letters come from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range (in particular, this is true for constant-sized alphabets).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] For larger alphabets, the running time is dominated by first sorting the letters to bring them into a range of size $O(n)$ ; in general, this takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The costs below are given under the assumption that the alphabet is constant.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Assume that a suffix tree has been built for the string S of length n , or that a generalised suffix tree has been built for the set of strings $D=\{S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{K}\}$ of total length $n=n_{1}+n_{2}+\cdots +n_{K}$ .
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The suffix tree can be prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval between nodes in $\Theta (n)$ time.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Suffix trees can be used to solve a large number of string problems that occur in text-editing, free-text search, computational biology and other application areas.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are often used in bioinformatics applications, searching for patterns in DNA or protein sequences (which can be viewed as long strings of characters).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The ability to search efficiently with mismatches might be considered their greatest strength.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are also used in data compression; they can be used to find repeated data, and can be used for the sorting stage of the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Variants of the LZW compression schemes use suffix trees (LZSS).
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] A suffix tree is also used in suffix tree clustering, a data clustering algorithm used in some search engines.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] If each node and edge can be represented in $\Theta (1)$ space, the entire tree can be represented in $\Theta (n)$ space.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The total length of all the strings on all of the edges in the tree is $O(n^{2})$ , but each edge can be stored as the position and length of a substring of S, giving a total space usage of $\Theta (n)$ computer words.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The worst-case space usage of a suffix tree is seen with a fibonacci word, giving the full $2n$ nodes.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] An important choice when making a suffix tree implementation is the parent-child relationships between nodes.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The most common is using linked lists called **sibling lists**.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Each node has a pointer to its first child, and to the next node in the child list it is a part of.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Other implementations with efficient running time properties use hash maps, sorted or unsorted arrays (with array doubling), or balanced search trees.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The insertion cost is amortised, and that the costs for hashing are given for perfect hashing.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The large amount of information in each edge and node makes the suffix tree very expensive, consuming about 10 to 20 times the memory size of the source text in good implementations.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Researchers have continued to find smaller indexing structures.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Various parallel algorithms to speed up suffix tree construction have been proposed.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Recently, a practical parallel algorithm for suffix tree construction with $O(n)$ work (sequential time) and $O(\log ^{2}n)$ span has been developed.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The algorithm achieves good parallel scalability on shared-memory multicore machines and can index the human genome – approximately 3GB – in under 3 minutes using a 40-core machine.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] Though linear, the memory usage of a suffix tree is significantly higher than the actual size of the sequence collection.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] For a large text, construction may require external memory approaches.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] There are theoretical results for constructing suffix trees in external memory.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The algorithm by Farach-Colton, Ferragina & Muthukrishnan (2000) is theoretically optimal, with an I/O complexity equal to that of sorting.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] However the overall intricacy of this algorithm has prevented, so far, its practical implementation.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] On the other hand, there have been practical works for constructing disk-based suffix trees which scale to (few) GB/hours.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The state of the art methods are TDD, TRELLIS, DiGeST, and B2ST.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] TDD and TRELLIS scale up to the entire human genome resulting in a disk-based suffix tree of a size in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] However, these methods cannot handle efficiently collections of sequences exceeding 3 GB.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] DiGeST performs significantly better and is able to handle collections of sequences in the order of 6 GB in about 6 hours.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] All these methods can efficiently build suffix trees for the case when the tree does not fit in main memory, but the input does.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] The most recent method, B2ST, scales to handle inputs that do not fit in main memory.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] ERA is a recent parallel suffix tree construction method that is significantly faster.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] ERA can index the entire human genome in 19 minutes on an 8-core desktop computer with 16 GB RAM.
[src:string-algorithms/suffix-tree] On a simple Linux cluster with 16 nodes (4 GB RAM per node), ERA can index the entire human genome in less than 9 minutes.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] In computer science, a **trie** (/ˈtraɪ/, /ˈtriː/ ⓘ), also known as a **digital tree** or **prefix tree**, is a specialized search tree data structure used to store and retrieve strings from a dictionary or set.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Unlike a binary search tree, nodes in a trie do not store their associated key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Instead, each node's *position* within the trie determines its associated key, with the connections between nodes defined by individual characters rather than the entire key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries are particularly effective for tasks such as autocomplete, spell checking, and IP routing, offering advantages over hash tables due to their prefix-based organization and lack of hash collisions.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Every child node shares a common prefix with its parent node, and the root node represents the empty string.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] While basic trie implementations can be memory-intensive, various optimization techniques such as compression and bitwise representations have been developed to improve their efficiency.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A notable optimization is the radix tree, which provides more efficient prefix-based storage.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] While tries store character strings, they can be adapted to work with any ordered sequence of elements, such as permutations of digits or shapes.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A notable variant is the **bitwise trie**, which uses individual bits from fixed-length binary data (such as integers or memory addresses) as keys.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The idea of a trie for representing a set of strings was first abstractly described by Axel Thue in 1912.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries were first described in a computer context by René de la Briandais in 1959.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The idea was independently described in 1960 by Edward Fredkin, who coined the term *trie*, pronouncing it /ˈtriː/ (as "tree"), after the middle syllable of *retrieval*.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] However, other authors pronounce it /ˈtraɪ/ (as "try"), in an attempt to distinguish it verbally from "tree".
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries are a form of string-indexed look-up data structure, which is used to store a dictionary list of words that can be searched on in a manner that allows for efficient generation of completion lists.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A prefix trie is an ordered tree data structure used in the representation of a set of strings over a finite alphabet set, which allows efficient storage of words with common prefixes.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries can be efficacious on string-searching algorithms such as predictive text, approximate string matching, and spell checking in comparison to binary search trees.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A trie can be seen as a tree-shaped deterministic finite automaton.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries support various operations: insertion, deletion, and lookup of a string key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries are composed of nodes that contain links, which either point to other suffix child nodes or *null*.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] As for every tree, each node except the root is pointed to by only one other node, called its *parent*.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Each node contains as many links as the number of characters in the applicable alphabet (although tries tend to have a substantial number of null links).
[src:string-algorithms/trie] In some cases, the alphabet used is simply that of the character encoding—resulting in, for example, a size of 128 in the case of ASCII.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Each node contains one possible link to a prefix of strong keys of the set.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A basic structure type of nodes in the trie is as follows: ${\text{Node}}$ may contain an optional ${\text{Value}}$ , which is associated with the key that corresponds to the node.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Searching for a value in a trie is guided by the characters in the search string key, as each node in the trie contains a corresponding link to each possible character in the given string.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Thus, following the string within the trie yields the associated value for the given string key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A null link during the search indicates the inexistence of the key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The following pseudocode implements the search procedure for a given string key in a rooted trie x.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] In the above pseudocode, x and key correspond to the pointer of the trie's root node and the string key, respectively.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The search operation takes $O(m)$ time, where m is the size of the string parameter key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] In a balanced binary search tree, on the other hand, it takes $O(m\log n)$ time, in the worst case, since key needs to be compared with $O(\log n)$ other keys and each comparison takes $O(m)$ time, in the worst case.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The trie occupies less space, in comparison with a binary search tree, in the case of a large number of short strings, since nodes share common initial string subsequences and store the keys implicitly.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Insertion into a trie is guided by using the character sets as indexes to the children array until the last character of the string key is reached.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Each node in the trie corresponds to one call of the radix sorting routine, as the trie structure reflects the execution pattern of the top-down radix sort.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] If null links are encountered before reaching the last character of the string key, new nodes are created.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The input value is assigned to the value of the last node traversed, which is the node that corresponds to the key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Deletion of a key–value pair from a trie involves finding the node corresponding to the key, setting its value to null, and recursively removing nodes that have no children.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The procedure begins by examining key; an empty string indicates arrival at the node corresponding to the (original) key, in which case its value is set to null.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] If the node, then, has null value and no children, it is removed from the trie by returning null; otherwise, the node is kept by returning the node itself.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] However, tries are less efficient than a hash table when the data is directly accessed on a secondary storage device such as a hard disk drive that has higher random access time than the main memory.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries can be represented in several ways, corresponding to different trade-offs between memory use and speed of the operations.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Using a vector of pointers for representing a trie consumes enormous space; however, memory space can be reduced at the expense of running time if a singly linked list is used for each node vector, as most entries of the vector contains ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Techniques such as *alphabet reduction* may reduce the large space requirements by reinterpreting the original string as a longer string over a smaller alphabet.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] For example, a string of n bytes can alternatively be regarded as a string of 2*n* four-bit units.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] This can reduce memory usage by a factor of eight; but lookups need to visit twice as many nodes in the worst case.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Another technique includes storing a vector of 256 ASCII pointers as a bitmap of 256 bits representing ASCII alphabet, which reduces the size of individual nodes dramatically.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Bitwise tries are used to address the enormous space requirement for the trie nodes in a naive simple pointer vector implementations.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Each character in the string key set is represented via individual bits, which are used to traverse the trie over a string key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The implementations for these types of trie use vectorized CPU instructions to find the first set bit in a fixed-length key input (e.g.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] GCC's `__builtin_clz()` intrinsic function).
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Accordingly, the set bit is used to index the first item, or child node, in the 32- or 64-entry based bitwise tree.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Search then proceeds by testing each subsequent bit in the key.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] This procedure is also cache-local and highly parallelizable due to register independency, and thus performant on out-of-order execution CPUs.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Radix tree, also known as a **compressed trie**, is a space-optimized variant of a trie in which any node with only one child gets merged with its parent; elimination of branches of the nodes with a single child results in better metrics in both space and time.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] This works best when the trie remains static and set of keys stored are very sparse within their representation space.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] One more approach for static tries is to "pack" the trie by storing disjoint sets of children in the same memory location, interleaved.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Patricia trees are a particular implementation of the compressed binary trie that uses the binary encoding of the string keys in its representation.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Every node in a Patricia tree contains an index, known as a "skip number", that stores the node's branching index to avoid empty subtrees during traversal.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A naive implementation of a trie consumes immense storage due to larger number of leaf-nodes caused by the sparse distribution of keys; Patricia trees can be efficient for such cases.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A representation of a Patricia tree is shown to the right.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Each index value adjacent to the nodes represents the "skip number"—the index of the bit with which branching is to be decided.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The skip number 1 at node 0 corresponds to the position 1 in the binary encoded ASCII where the leftmost bit differed in the key set X.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The skip number is crucial for search, insertion, and deletion of nodes in the Patricia tree, and a bit masking operation is performed during every iteration.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Trie data structures are commonly used in predictive text or autocomplete dictionaries, and approximate matching algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries enable faster searches, occupy less space, especially when the set contains large number of short strings, thus used in spell checking, hyphenation applications and longest prefix match algorithms.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] However, if storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e. there is no need to store metadata associated with each word), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) or radix tree would use less storage space than a trie.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] This is because DAFSAs and radix trees can compress identical branches from the trie that correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] String dictionaries are also utilized in natural language processing, such as finding lexicon of a text corpus.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Lexicographic sorting of a set of string keys can be implemented by building a trie for the given keys and traversing the tree in pre-order fashion; this is also a form of radix sort.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries are also fundamental data structures for burstsort, which is notable for being the fastest string sorting algorithm as of 2007, accomplished by its efficient use of CPU cache.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A special kind of trie, called a suffix tree, can be used to index all suffixes in a text to carry out fast full-text searches.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] A specialized kind of trie called a compressed trie, is used in web search engines for storing the indexes - a collection of all searchable words.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Each terminal node is associated with a list of URLs—called occurrence list—to pages that match the keyword.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] The trie is stored in the main memory, whereas the occurrence is kept in an external storage, frequently in large clusters, or the in-memory index points to documents stored in an external location.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Tries are used in Bioinformatics, notably in sequence alignment software applications such as BLAST, which indexes all the different substrings of length *k* (called k-mers) of a text by storing the positions of their occurrences in a compressed trie sequence databases.
[src:string-algorithms/trie] Compressed variants of tries, such as databases for managing Forwarding Information Base (FIB), are used in storing IP address prefixes within routers and bridges for prefix-based lookup to resolve mask-based operations in IP routing.
